Retry: Yes, but in the case of making items, each failure ruins the half the raw materials needed, and the character has to pay half the raw material cost again. For identifying substances or potions, each failure consumes the cost per attempt.
\par Special: The character must have alchemical equipment to make an item or identify it. For identifying items, the cost represen
ts additional supplies the character must buy. Purchasing and maintaining an alchemist's lab grants a +2 circumstance bonus to Alchemy checks (from the favorable condition of having the perfect tools for the job) but does not affect the cost of any items 
made using the skill.
\par }{\fcs1 \ai\af0 \fcs0 \cs18\i\insrsid15551003 Animal Empathy (CHA; TRAINED ONLY; DRUID, RANGER ONLY)}{\fcs1 \af0 \fcs0 \insrsid15551003 
\par Check: The character can improve the attitude of an animal with a successful check. To use the skill, the character and the animal must be able to study each other, noting each oth
er's body language, vocalizations, and general demeanor. This means that the character must be within 30 feet under normal conditions.
\par Generally, influencing an animal in this way takes 1 minute, but, as with influencing people, it might take more or less time.
\par This skill works on animals. The character can use it with a \endash 4 penalty on beasts and magical beasts.
\par Retry: As with attempts to influence people, retries on the same animal generally don't work (or don't work any better), whether the character has succeeded or not.
\par }{\fcs1 \ai\af0 \fcs0 \cs18\i\insrsid15551003 Appraise (INT)}{\fcs1 \af0 \fcs0 \insrsid15551003 
\par Check: The character can appraise common or well-known objects within 10% of their value (DC 12). Failure means the character estimates the value at 50% to 150% of actual value. The DM secretly rolls 2d6+3, multiplies by 10%
, multiplies the actual value by that percentage, and tells the character that value for the item. (For a common or well-known item, the character's chance of estimating the value within 10% is fairly high even if the character fails the check\emdash 
in such a case, the character made a lucky guess.)
\par Rare or exotic items require a successful check against DC 15, 20, or higher. If successful, the character estimates the value at 70% to 130% of its actual value. The DM secretly rolls 2d4+5, multiplies by 10%, multip
lies the actual value by that percentage, and tells the character that value for the item. Failure means the character cannot estimate the item's value.
\par A magnifying glass gives a +2 circumstance bonus to Appraise checks involving any item that is small or
 highly detailed, such as a gem. A merchant's scale gives a +2 circumstance bonus to Appraise checks involving any items that are valued by weight, including anything made of precious metals. These bonuses stack.
\par Appraising an item takes 1 minute.
\par Retry: Not on the same object, regardless of success.
\par Special: If the character is making the check untrained, for common items, failure means no estimate, and for rare items, success means an estimate of 50% to 150% (2d6+3 times 10%).
\par }{\fcs1 \ai\af0 \fcs0 \cs18\i\insrsid15551003 Balance (DEX; ARMOR CHECK PENALTY)}{\fcs1 \af0 \fcs0 \insrsid15551003 
\par Check: The character can walk on a precarious surface as a move-equivalent action. A successful check lets the character move at half the character's speed along the surface for 1 round. A failure means that the character can't move for 1 round. A f
ailure by 5 or more means that the character falls. 
\par The difficulty varies with the surface:
